  "buggy_files": ["sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c"],
  "buggy_functions": ["azx_resume", "azx_rirb_get_response"],
  "confidence": 0.95,
  "reasoning": "The HDA Intel driver sets chip->single_cmd=1 and chip->polling_mode=1 in azx_rirb_get_response when codec communication times out. These flags enable degraded communication modes but are never reset. During suspend, the chip is stopped (chip->initialized=0), but the degradation flags persist. During resume in azx_resume, azx_init_chip is called to reinitialize, but it skips CORB/RIRB initialization if chip->single_cmd is still set (line 1222-1223). This causes the codec to remain in degraded mode after waking from suspend, resulting in choppy audio and continued timeouts. The fix requires resetting chip->single_cmd, chip->polling_mode, and chip->poll_count to 0 in azx_resume before calling azx_init_chip, allowing proper re-initialization of the CORB/RIRB communication channel after resume."
}

